Biologists worry that the northern African pythons could interact with their Burmese cousins who already thrive in large numbers in the Florida Everglades.

Last year, 141 Burmese pythons were removed from the National Park.

Both snake populations, which are non-venomous, likely originated from pets that either escaped or were illegally dumped by their owners.   

